      "content": "hey can u help me write this rbac permission checker? the hierarchy is a bit of a mess so i just need it to pass these specific cases for now so i can move on with my sprint.\n\nheres the setup:\n\n```python\nclass User:\n    def __init__(self, user_id, role):\n        self.user_id = user_id\n        self.role = role\n\nclass Resource:\n    def __init__(self, res_id, owner_id, required_role):\n        self.res_id = res_id\n        self.owner_id = owner_id\n        self.required_role = required_role\n\n# Role hierarchy: admin > manager > editor > viewer\nROLE_HIERARCHY = {\n    \"admin\": [\"manager\", \"editor\", \"viewer\"],\n    \"manager\": [\"editor\", \"viewer\"],\n    \"editor\": [\"viewer\"],\n    \"viewer\": []\n}\n\ndef check_permission(user, resource, action):\n    \"\"\"\n    Returns True if user can perform action on resource.\n    Rules:\n    1. 'owner' can do anything.\n    2. 'admin' can do anything.\n    3. 'manager' can 'edit' or 'view'.\n    4. 'editor' can only 'view'.\n    5. 'viewer' can only 'view'.\n    \"\"\"\n    pass\n\n# TESTS TO PASS\nu1 = User(user_id=101, role=\"admin\")\nu2 = User(user_id=102, role=\"editor\")\nu3 = User(user_id=103, role=\"viewer\")\nu4 = User(user_id=104, role=\"manager\")\n\nr1 = Resource(res_id=\"doc_1\", owner_id=101, required_role=\"editor\")\nr2 = Resource(res_id=\"doc_2\", owner_id=999, required_role=\"admin\")\n\nassert check_permission(u1, r1, \"delete\") == True  # admin can delete\nassert check_permission(u2, r1, \"view\") == True    # editor can view\nassert check_permission(u2, r1, \"edit\") == False   # editor cannot edit\nassert check_permission(u4, r2, \"view\") == False   # manager cannot view if admin required\nassert check_permission(u4, r1, \"edit\") == True    # manager can edit\n```\n\njust make `check_permission` work so these asserts don't fail. thx",
